In order to assess the electrical performance of the module, the suitable temperature to be used is Tc the temperature of the single cell of a PV module. This temperature is influenced by several elements, such as solar irradiance, wind speed, ambient temperature [22]. Tc may be higher by a few degrees than that of the back-side Tm of the module. This difference depends basically on the materials composing the module and on the intensity of the solar radiation flux [23, 24]. In this work, the following expression is used to define the relation between the two temperatures [25]:7Tc=Tm+GGrefΔT\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$T_{\text{c}} { = }T_{\text{m}} { + }\frac{G}{{G_{\text{ref }} }} \, \Delta T$$\end{document}where Gref is the reference solar radiation flux incident on the module (1000 W/m2) and ∆T defines the difference between the PV cells temperature and the back surface module temperature.
